-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Namibia Climbs, Mumias Sugar of Kenya Is Active
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 2011-02-03T15:55:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-03/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenolkobil-mumias-sugar-are-active.html
  Kenya ’s All-Share Index rose for the
first day in six, adding 0.5 percent to 78.89 by the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index fell 0.1
percent to 26,895.35 by the close at 2:30 p.m. in Lagos,
according to an e-mailed statement from the bourse. The Ghana
Stock Exchange Composite Index advanced for a second day,
increasing 0.8 percent to close at 1,059.28 by 3 p.m. in Accra,
while Namibia’s FTSE  Namibia Overall Index  climbed for a third
day, rising 1.1 percent to 913.02 by 5 p.m. in Windhoek, the
highest since July 2008.  Mauritius’s stock exchange was closed for a public holiday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Mumias Sugar Co. (MSUG KN), Kenya’s biggest maker of the
sweetener, gained for the first time since Jan. 18, rising 40
cents, or 4.7 percent, to 8.90 shillings on speculation earnings
will improve in the second half of the financial year, Eric Musau, an analyst at African Alliance Securities Kenya Ltd.,
said in a phone interview from Nairobi.  Net income for the six months through December dropped 22
percent to 816.3 million shillings ($10 million), it said on
Jan. 31. The second half will be “significantly better” and
full-year earnings will increase on a year earlier, it said.  To contact the reporters on this story:
